  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a broad international consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a serious criminal offense because it involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. This process allows criminals to integrate illicit funds into the financial system, making them appear legitimate.\n\nMost countries have established legal frameworks to combat money laundering, often in line with international standards and agreements. Key international organizations and agreements that promote anti-money laundering (AML) efforts include:\n\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: An intergovernmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. The FATF's recommendations are widely adopted by member countries.\n\n2. **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention)**: This convention includes provisions to combat money laundering.\n\n3. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**: Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering through effective risk management and compliance practices.\n\n4. **European Union Directives**: The EU has issued several anti-money laundering directives that member states are required to implement into their national laws.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is illegal in virtually every jurisdiction around the world, and there is strong international cooperation to combat it through comprehensive legal and regulatory frameworks.",
